Comparison of different-sized cities using the number of Starbucks stores and coffee shops¶

Description of Problem and Background¶

From the FourSquare API, we are able to query different venue categories and venue names when we want to search for all nearby venues for a given (latitude, longitude) location. However, since we are only able to query up to 100 nearby venues using the free edition of the API, I want to find a defining venue to unqiuely identify and encompass some of the key characteristics of a given neighbourhood of a particular city. As a heavy coffee drinker myself, one of the first idea that came to mind is perhaps compare the frequency of the number of Starbucks stores as some sort of metric to idenity a neighbourhood. However, since the number of stores is going to vary greatly from city to city (depending on the city size, population, and the individuals' coffee preference), it would be more sensible to normalize this frequency by taking the ratio of the number of Starbucks stores to total number of all other coffee stores.

The hypothesis is that "similar" neighbourds from different cities could be clustered together using this Starbucks store ratio, i.e., Toronto and New York should have a more similar Starbucks store ratio, compared to Toronto and Vaughan (a smaller city in Ontario), given their city sizes, population density, cost of living etc.

Description of the Data¶

First, we will use the FourSquare API to get a list of all the nearby venues of "coffee shops" for each city. This can be achieved by adding a query parameter when making the API call (i.e., query = "coffee shop"). Then, we will get a count of all nearby Starbucks store and also a count of all other nearby coffee stores for a given city (region). This can be done by applying a one-hot encoder (i.e., 1 for Starbucks and 0 for other coffee shops).

Methodology¶

Data Exploration using Toronto as an example¶

First, we will use the city of Toronto as an example to perform some exploratory analysis.

We will now use the wikipedia page of postal codes in Canada to get a list of all postal codes in Canada to get the longitude and latitudes of each Borough. Notice that we did this here because FourSquare API will limit each location's reulsts to a maximum of 100 venues for each given location of latitude and longtitude. In other words, if we simply use Toronto in the API call, we will only have a maximum of 100 nearby venues for the given latitude and longtitude of Toronto. However, if we break down the city into different Boroughs, then use each individual Borough as a unique API for latitude and longtitude, we can obtain a maximum of 100 nearby venues for each Borough.

# define a function that extracts the category of all nearby venues with radius 500
def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius=500):
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(name)
        query = "coffee shop"
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}&query={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT,
            query)
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])
    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  'Neighborhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighborhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

Some potential problems and suggested fix¶

We are able to obtain a final ratio of Starbucks to non-Starbucks coffee shops to be about 20%. However, this method of mapping each borough to their corresponding latitudes and longtitude using the wikipedia page for each city isn't scalable. Hence, I have decided to just take the first 100 nearby venues whenever we call the FourSquare API on a given city name. This should also be representative for the entire city. We will also create a function that takes in a city name and returns number of Starbucks store and number of other coffee stores.

In [67]:
def starbucks_ratio(city):
#     city = 'Toronto, Canada'
    geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="toronto_explorer")
    location = geolocator.geocode(city)
    latitude = location.latitude
    longitude = location.longitude
    print('The geograpical coordinate of {} are {}, {}.'.format(city, latitude, longitude))
    radius=500
    LIMIT=100
    query= "coffee shop"
    # create the API request URL
    url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}&query={}'.format(
        CLIENT_ID, 
        CLIENT_SECRET, 
        VERSION, 
        latitude, 
        longitude, 
        radius, 
        LIMIT,
        query)
    # make the GET request
    results = requests.get(url).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
    if results:
        venues_list=[]
        venues_list.append([(
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])
        nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
        nearby_venues.columns = ['Venue', "Venue Latitude","Venue Longitude", "Venue Category"]
        nearby_venues

        nearby_venues["Starbucks_bool"] = nearby_venues["Venue"].apply(lambda x: 1 if "Starbucks" in x else 0)
        num_all_stores = len(nearby_venues["Starbucks_bool"])
        starbucks_freq = len(nearby_venues.loc[nearby_venues["Starbucks_bool"] == 1])/num_all_stores
        num_starbucks = len(nearby_venues.loc[nearby_venues["Starbucks_bool"] == 1])
        num_others = len(nearby_venues.loc[nearby_venues["Starbucks_bool"] == 0])
    else:
        starbucks_freq = 0
    print(f"ratio of Starbucks to other coffee shops: {starbucks_freq}, num_starbucks: {num_starbucks}, num_others: {num_others}")
    return num_starbucks, num_others

Discussion¶

Now, we will apply a kmeans clustering algorithm, with number of clusters equal to 2, hoping to cluster/label each cities using their Starbucks to other coffee shops ratio.

In [172]:
k_means = KMeans(init="k-means++", n_clusters=2, n_init=12)
X = np.column_stack((num_starbucks_lst, num_others_lst))
k_means.fit(X)
y_kmeans = k_means.predict(X)
In [173]:
plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis')
centers = k_means.cluster_centers_
plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='red', s=50, alpha=0.5)
for i, city_name in enumerate(cities):
    plt.annotate(city_name, (num_starbucks_lst[i], num_others_lst[i]))
plt.gcf().set_size_inches((10, 10))

Finally, we can see that the kmeans algorithm, have more or less clustered the cities based on the population, with the yellow labeled colors being cities with large populations, and purple being the smaller sized cities. The red dots represents the two centroid for the two clusters.

Conclusion¶

After we added these international cities, and setting the number of clusters = 3 for our k-means algorithm, we can observe a somewhat similar result to the Ontario cites clusters, i.e., similar-sized cities are more or less grouped together in the same cluster. However, there are some discrepnacy as well, namely "New York" and "Paris".

This could be due to various geo-politcal and cultural reasons (and not just limited to population size/density), such as whether or not the people in these cities are less passionate about drinking coffee, or maybe there other pre-dominant chain coffee baristas other than Starbucks (i.e., perhaps people in New York or Paris are more likely to support local baristas), or simply due to the overall Starbucks company policy at different cities/regions.

Overall, we can conclude that there is indeed some relationship between a city's population and its "Starbucks to other coffee shops" ratio, but other factors might need to be considered as well. Hence, some recommended follow up could be adding other geo-politcal/cultural features to our clustering algorithm rather than just population density, such as "cost of living", etc.
